t=25>Next Page</a></td></tr></table></form><a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=10>Root thread</a><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10180256144470>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=>RE: ranger asks ranger questions to other rangers</a> <a id=fs8 href=#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Fri, Apr 5th 11:53 AM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=77541><span id=Scholar>blowfish</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>227 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.20]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>The Ranger - well I've always loved playing rangers, from table top D+D type games, through many single player RPG type games where you play one charachter, to the games where you control a group of 6 players (why is always 6??). And it would always be rangers, Bladders Gate, ranger, Diablo, ranger type, all those PC RPG's i forget the names for etc etc., and then I found EQ, and am still looking for that golden group of 6 rangers!! So why rangers, well to honest I've never really analysed it before but when you think about it, in terms of game mechanics rangers just have more to do!! I'm talking about how many skills you have at your fingers tips and how often, during a melee (or pull) you have to make decisions. Warriors, what I just press autoattack and thats it? Oh I get to press kick too! Fun. Seriously, Warriors could run a creche while playing, it's just a shame that verant didn't make it so that the autoattack stays on after the first Mob has died, then they could make dinner too. Double Fun! Then there's the majourity of casters, throughout all these games it's conservation of mana, more like accountancy than any other discipline, at least verant developed the aggro system so they have the thrill of the risk of being battered to snot. No wonder they took the book away, at least they can watch the fight (I know there exceptions, chanters mezzing etc, but you get the point). Theives/Rogues have the tactical backstab to work with but once that's in they just cross there fingers and hope they don't get too much aggro. The other hybrids, pallies probably get the best roleplaying, but generally speaking they mostly tanks with one other good trick up their sleeves. Monks have always been a mystery to me so I will leave them out of this apart from to say that maybe the are just enigmatic tanks. Bards are possibly the exception in EQ, they always look busy, changing songs around and stuff. Now I'm not saying this to 'flame' the other classes, all I'm saying is that while playing a ranger (well) you have to be constantly on your toes, and&nbsp;&nbsp;verant I think have made them more 'busy' to play than ever before. Not only do you have the usual array of skills and decisions to make, but also ranger's seem the only class to have the ability to really manage aggro, a group without a ranger merely copes with it, we deal with it, taking it, giving it away, making the rogues happy, looking after the casters etc. Also verant has really beefed up the bow abilities of rangers, offering a whole new 'range' of possibilities and decisions. Then there's all the other stuff that our spells allow us to do, a million and one ways to pull, aggro management, the utilities we share with the other hybrids and the ones we don't. <br>  In a nutshell, when you play a ranger, there is never a dull moment and it should never be repetitive as you adapt to the way the battle changes, root that add, snare that one before it runs, flamelick the caster mob, save the wizzies skin. If you have downtime, keeping an eye on your self cast buffs and even being a baby healer when necessary. That's what I think makes being a ranger so much fun, and so addictive, there are just so many more factors to juggle with, so many decisions to be made and at the end of the day, so many buttons to press! I have 4 alts, they are all rangers!!!! <br><br>Please toast me if you think I am wrong in any of this, it's just discussion.<br><br>As for your questions, <br>Luclin I can't help you with. <br>There are some great lvl guides at the rangers glade site, the link is down a bit in one of the sages posts, however, there are many viable ways to carve you're way through, so explore explore explore and take the guides to give you limits of where not to go just yet. <br>As for tips, I have one that I have just discovered and am thinking of exploiting and would appreciate other peoples opinions on, it is to do with the Trueshot Longbow. Now, fletching, as far as I see it is the easiest skill to start out, I don't see any other skill you can take from 0 to 120 in an hour with just 200 plat and superhuman patience to just keep clicking, but then comes the Truesot!! What a pain! A lot of running around and then half the bits are no drop so you can't take shortcuts, you can't get anybody else to make it for you and when you have made it (minimum fletch skill about 150 - unless you get lucky) and it is lore so when you have made one, after some 20 failed attempts in my case, you can only have that one. But they do sell for a good price, about 200pp I understand which is cool. So  I made as many alts as I could, nekkid wood elfs, and gave them one each, they now just sit in kelethin waitng for friends and family to pick them up. But for a younger ranger, if you get your fletching skill up early, which would mean diverting a lot of cash away from armour, the hardest mob is not too hard and this could be a way of making some plat. Just load the alts up and then sell the bows one by one, and then get a good friend to transfer the cash, - bingo maybe 1kpp if you have 5 slots free. What do you think?<br><br>Anyway, help that was hopeful maximos, good luck and happy hunting.</p>&nbsp;<br>Hello Mr %T, time to die.<br><br>Rainingdog Sandcats - Xev</td></td></tr>
